REC WAF 2023 ACTIVITY TRACKER ANALYSIS

Author

RECWAF PMEL Team

1 Number of Activities

Majority of the activities done from January 2023 till date are related to training and capacity building followed by Sensitisation.

Majority of the activities conducted within the REC from January are related to training and sensitisation. Most of the training in the REC have been contributed from Ghana and Nigeria.

2 Number of Activities per Project

The number and types of activities carried out in the REC from January 2023 to date in project is found in the table below. It is evident that the heavy training is mainly contributed by the following projects in Ghana - COCOLIFE, ACTING NOW and NORAD.

3 Activities and Project Participant Types

As at the end of third quarter,farmers were the primary beneficiaries of the activities carried out , followed by community members, VSLA groups, and other kinds of project participants, as shown in the graphs below, however, different projects have reached diverse types of target groups.

4 Participants Engaged by the Various Projects in the REC

The graph below presents a distribution of the various project participants engaged per project.

5 Number of Project Participants - Training & Meetings

As at end of the third quarter, the REC currently has close to a 50:50 male to female ratio for the individual direct project participants. KERING-EGF in Ghana has the highest proportion (100%) of women, given the project is focused on females in mining communities followed by FVO SHEA(99.1%) and then Gender RAI (88.2%) in Sierra Leone. Nigeria has the highest proportion of target project participants (57.4%) to be females followed by Ghana(49.8%).

7 Sensitisation

Similar to direct beneficiaries, sensitizations carried out in Nigeria and Sierra Leone presently have almost equal proportion of estimated reach of males and females.

The sensitization campaigns have focused mostly on climate smart agriculture , child labor, home gardening,land policies, sanitation, gender issues, and promoting fruit and vegetables as a business

9 VSLA Engagements

Since January, a total of 92 VSLA engagements have been executed, most of which were done under the Cocolife project in Ghana.

The VSLA reports submitted so far for this year are mostly pertaining to VSLA Activity tracking.

Backstopping was the most prevalent form of assistance provided to VSLAs during facilitation visits by both the Cocoalife and Better Chicken projects.

10 Items Distributed

As at the end of the third quarter, various items including agrochemicals , pruning tools , sprouted seeds , fertilizers, seedlings and VSLA boxes have been distributed to project participants across five projects as shown in the graph below :

Ghana COCOLIFE Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Cocoa These 9 farmers were visited in their various farms and issues identified included; 1. Mealy pod rot caused by Trachysphaera fructigena. 2. Brown spots on cocoa becoming darker each day. 3. Increasing spread of backpod disease. 4. Presence of ants eating cocoa pods. Solutions were given out to each of these challenges faced by the farmers. There were demonstrations on which Fungicide to apply and the right quantity to use. Other Cultural and chemical control methods were also taught. NA NA
Ghana COCOLIFE Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Cocoa 1. For crop management, climate smart agriculture practices that will be useful include : a. Intercropping b. Crop rotation c. Planting of new crop varieties d. Improvement in processing techniques and storage 2. For soil and water management, the practice below will be useful. a. Conservative agriculture b. Improved irrigation c. Water storage d. Contour planting 3. For livestock and agro forestry management, the following will be useful. a. Improved feeding strategies b. Fodder crops c. Livestock health d. Multipurpose trees NA Since climate smart agriculture is a newly evolved production system for agriculture, training farmers should be done all year round in order to ensure its practices.

Ghana COCOLIFE Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Cocoa Training of farmers on farming as a business typically emphasized on financial management, market analysis, crop selection, and value added opportunities. Participants learned to view their farms as enterprises, focusing on profitability and sustainability. Proper record keeping were highlighted to help farmers make informed decisions and maximize their returns. NA 1. Moving forward, focus should be on financial management, budgeting, and cost analysis to help farmers understand and manage their farms effectively. 2. Farmer's should be taught how to conduct market research to identify demand, and potential buyers for their products. 3. Much emphasis should be made on the importance of diversifying crops to manage risk and explore multiple revenue streams. 4. The importance of accurate record-keeping for tracking expenses, yield, and profitability should be stressed on. 5. Farmers should be directed towards creating a comprehensive business plan that outlines goals, strategies, and financial projections.

Farmers adopt sustainable and resilient agriculture practices that conserve resources, enhance soil health, and reduce emissions. 3. Improved yields and resources management can result in increased income and reduced input costs for farmers. In so doing farmers will be very much aware of its sustainable practices which will intend increase food security.

The community acknowledged the achievements made since the last review, highlighting successful initiatives and project that have positively impacted the community. 2. It was agreed that certain aspects of the action plan needed adjustment based on the current community needs and changing circumstances. 3. A refined leadership strategy was used to ensure effective dissemination of responsibilities to community members keeping them engaged in the progress of the action plan. 4. CAPs Review dissemination revolved around ensuring the sustainability of the plans initiatives beyond the initial implementation period, explaining awareness for continued funding and support. No challenges were faced during the review but various challenges and obstacles were discussed, including resource constraints, communication gaps, and external factors affecting the plans implementation. 1. The importance of collaboration with local organization, Stakeholders, and volunteers was emphasized as a means to leverage expertise and resources for better outcome. 2. The need for a good monitoring and evaluation framework is to be used for regular assessment of progress and identification of areas that require further attention.

Ghana COCOLIFE Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Cocoa From the training, several conclusions can be drawn : 1. Participants likely acquire improved skills in advocacy, Lobbying, and fundraising techniques enabling them to effectively engage with potential donors and advocate for their cause. 2. Training in these areas can lead to heightened awareness among participants about the importance of advocacy, lobbying, and fundraising in achieving community goals. 3. CODEC members develop a more strategic approach to fundraising and advocacy, utilizing the tools and techniques learned during the training to create impact full campaigns. 4. CODEC members after the training have gained confidence in their ability to approach fundraising and advocacy challenges, leading to more successful outcomes. 5. Training has helped CODEC members refine their messaging, ensuring that their fundraising and advocacy efforts effectively. No challenges were faced. From this training several recommendations were made: 1. Tailored Strategies Tailor your fundraising and advocacy strategies to your community specific goals, Community members, and mission. One- size-fit- all approach may not be as effective. 2. Diversified Funding Sources Knowledge on fundraising and advocacy will explore a variety of fundraising sources including individuals donors, grants, and corporate sponsorship. 3. Advocacy Techniques Implement a mix of advocacy techniques such as lobbying, grassroot organizing, and public awareness campaigns to amplify your cause's message. 4. Building Relationships Participants were taught to focus on building authentic relationships with donors, supporters, and collaborators. A strong network can lead to sustained support and partnership.

Ghana GENDER Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Gender The training on the Gender Action Learning System (GALS) was informative, detailed and educational. Participants gained a solid understanding of GALS principles and methodologies. The primary challenge was the limited allocated time of two days for the training. This time constraint posed difficulties due to the extensive nature of the training material. It is advisable to extend the training duration to allow for a more comprehensive exploration of GALS concepts and methodologies. Following the training, there is the need to have a refresher training program for those who have completed the initial training to keep them updated with the latest GALS tools and ensure continued proficiency in its application.

Nigeria ACTING NOW Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Potatoes On the 21st July, 2023, the second engagement meeting took place. With twenty (20) participants in attendance. The participants were taking through the second module of the training manual. The second module is a whole new concept for the farmers, as most of the concepts are new to them especially, rooted apical cuttings, transplanting plantlets in the screen house and aerophonics. The have no idea about these concepts. A lot of questions were asked and answered were provided by I the facilitator. The training session was not interactive as most of the concepts were new to the participants. Most of the participants were interested about the new varieties of potato and how they can purchase it. The participants were directed to National root crops research institute (NRCRI) and fruit and veggies global limited (FVGL) for the new improve seedlings. Generally, it was a successful training session and new ideas were learned. Lack of training manuals made it difficult for the participants to see the pictures of the apical cuttings and aeroponic technology seed potato production which was new to the participants. Availability of training manuals will enhance effective learning.
Nigeria ACTING NOW Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Potatoes On the 20th of July, 2023, the second engagement meeting took place at Washen community bokkos LGA. Twenty two(22) female participants were in attendance. The farmers were taking through the second module of the training manual. The second module is quite different from the normal potato seed generation and preservation that the farmers are familiar with. Most of the concepts were new to the farmers such as: Rooted apical cuttings, Transplanting plantlets in the screen house and Aeroponics technology seed potato production. At the end of the training question were been asked and answers were provided by the facilitator. After the training session, the farmers have now learned the benefits of generating their own seedlings and how to preserved it. Most of the participants were making enquiry on how to purchase the new improve varieties of seedlings. Lack of training manual to make the training session more participatory. Availability of training manuals will enhance effective learning.

The participants were surprised about the most of the concepts especially, rooted apical cuttings, transplanting plantlets in the screen house, and aeroponics technology seed production. Nigeria ACTING NOW Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Potatoes On the 11th August, 2023.The fourth training session held at Kupiyel-Taragol. Fifteen (15) male participants were in attendance. We went through, module four of the training manual which covers potato pests and symptoms and management. As one of the main problem most farmers encounter over the years. Participants paid keen interest throughout the course of discussions and were eager to try out the control management practices outlined. However, the fact that most of the insecticides to use were only mentioned in general terms without specifications. It was a major problem encountered as participants voiced out their concerns on several chemical control method they have used without any success. And have wished for a higher solution is proffered. During the training session, some questions were asked by the farmers, such as: (1) What if a person has only one farmland, without any substitute and that farm has been infected by Potato Cyst Nematode(PCN) which usually lives in the soil for more than twenty years? (2) what are the names of insecticide and pesticides that a farmer can use to control these pests and insects? (3) What are the natural methods of controlling cutworms? I the facilitator responded to two of the question, that is, question (1&3) while the third question I will have to ask Mr Kahya. Question one I responded by advising the farmers to practice crop rotation. They should plant another crop that is resistant to PCN, for example, maize millet or soya beans. While the third question I advised the farmers to till the soil and practice solarization method. Lastly, it was a successful training session. Persistent rainfall which caused late arrival of the participants to the training venue. Availability of training manual will enhance effective learning.
Nigeria ACTING NOW Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Potatoes On the 11th August, 2023.The fourth training session held at Kupiyel-Taragol. Thirteen (13) female participants were in attendance. We went through, module four of the training manual which covers potato pests symptoms and management . As one of the main problem most farmers encounter over the years. Participants paid keen interest throughout the course of discussions and were eager to try out the control management practices outlined. However, the fact that most of the insecticides to use were only mentioned in general terms without specifications. It was a major problem encountered as participants voiced out their concerns on several chemical control method they have used without any success. And have wished for a higher solution is proffered. During the training session, some questions were asked by the farmers, such as: (1) what if, a farmer stores his or her potato tuber in the store without sanitizing the store first? And the farmer notices some symptoms of Potato Tuber Moth ( PTM) in the store. what will be the solution? (2) What are some of the control method the farmer can use, to get rid of white grubs from his or her farmland? I the facilitator responded to two of the question, that is, question (1&2) . Question one I responded by encouraging the farmers to practice good sanitation habit. Before bring the tubers to the store they should sanitize the store with the right chemicals so as, to kill the PTM and the larvas or by the use of lantana plants. While the second question, I advised the farmers to make proper drainage. Because White grubs prefer moist soil especially with high content of decaying organic matter and also they should practice solarization method too. Lastly, it was an interactive session. Persistent rainfall. Availability of training manual will enhance effective learning.
Nigeria ACTING NOW Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Potatoes On the 10th August, 2023. The fourth training session took place at Washen community bokkos, LGA. Eighteen (18) male participants were in attendance. The participants, were taken through the fourth module of the training manual. which we looked at potato pests, symptoms and management. Potato pests have been a major problem of Potato production in most rural communities. The farmers, listened carefully as the paid attention to the training. In the course of discussions the farmers contributed as they may have identified most of the pests, listed in the training manual on their farms. But do not have ideas on how to control or destroy the pests. Although, they have used different chemicals but there was no positive outcomes. The farmers were anxious to learn and practice the control method on their farms, so as to reduce the caused of loss of Potato tubers in the field and store. Some few questions were asked by the farmers. Such as; (1) what if, a farmer notices any symptoms of Aphids on his or her farmland, what are the methods to control it? (2) What are the names of insecticide that can be use to control tuber moth? I, the facilitator responded to the first question. By encouraging the farmers to make use of certified seeds. That control Aphids and the viral diseases. Another method is by removing the affected plants where aphids have invaded a potato crop and lastly, to control aphids the farmer can make use of biological control by using lady bird beetles and wasps. For the second question, i advised the farmers to make use of chemicals containing Cypermetrin and actellic these chemicals can destroy but the Moth and the larvae. It was a participatory session. With the men group. Bad roads. Availability of training manual will enhance effective learning.
Nigeria ACTING NOW Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Potatoes On the 10th August, 2023. The fourth training session held at Washen community bokkos, LGA. Eighteen (18) female participants were in attendance. The farmers were, taken through the fourth module of the training manual. Which covers the aspects of Potato pests, symptoms and management. This module is one of important topic to the farmers as the farmers have been experiencing difficulties on how to control potato pest. During the training session, most participants expressed reasonable knowledge of the pests out listed, the insects were common to the farmers cause they must have seen the insects on their farms. However, since the farmers were open to learning they paid keen attention to the discussions and also related it to their already existing farmlands. Some few questions were asked by the participants. Such as; (1)What if, a farmer has only one farmland and it's been infected by Potato cyst Nematode and he or she has been using the land for potato production? (2) What are the control method, for controlling white grubs? The first question is the most common question I encounter during the cause of my training with the farmers. But I always advised the farmers to practice crop rotation. Because Potato cyst Nematode, can last for twenty years in the soil. But once it lacks what to eat, which will sustain it for a longer period of time PCN will definitely starve to death or move to another location. Another way to control Potato cyst Nematode is to destroy volunteer crops that is, unwanted crops or crops from last season. And also practice strict farm hygiene. I responded to the second question. By urging the farmers to always till the soil deeply to exposes the grubs to the sunlight. Another method is to ensure proper drainage because white grubs prefer moist soil. The training session was educative and participatory. Bad roads. Availability of training manual will enhance effective learning.
Nigeria ACTING NOW Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Potatoes On the 10th of August, 2023. The fourth training session took place at Washen community bokkos LGA. Eleven (11) Male and female youths were in attendance. Participants, were taken through the fourth module of the training manual which covers the aspects of Potato pests, symptoms and management. When it comes to the issue of pests it is one of the biggest challenges farmers have been going through over the years. During the cause of discussions farmers voice out there personal experiences with different pests and how it has caused a lot of damages to the potato tubers both in the field and even in their various stores. The farmers willingness to learn shows that they are willing to implement the ideas on their farms. Some few questions were asked by the farmers, such as; (1) What factors necessitate the spread of the pests. (2) Do the pests residence in the farms or they usually come from somewhere to infect the crops. The first question is regarding the generally control of the five pests we discussed during our training with the farmers. These five pests have one thing in common they all feed on potato crop, from the leaves, stem, root and the tubers and solanaceous crops. Once the pests start getting their food they can survive and keep on multiplying and can last for a longer period of years. I responded to the question by encouraging the farmers to make proper drainage because most pests can be wash from other farms to their farms. And also some of the pests can live in the soil for twenty years, for example Potato cyst Nematode and will keep on feeding on the crops. Bad roads. Availability of training manual will enhance effective learning.

Became pests are one of the most difficult challenges the farmers encounter both in the field and stores. (2) what are the specific insecticide and pesticides to use to control Cutworms. Once these eggs hatches, the larvae with enter the tuber through the eye. And cause damages to the tubers. The second question, I responded by advising the farmers to purchase insecticide and pesticides which contains cyper- metrin and actellic. Specific name of the insecticide and pesticides was not listed in the training manual that's is for Pests. I promised the farmers to make enquiries and get back to them on the specific names of chemicals to use. Generally, it was a participatory session. Persistent rainfall. Nigeria ACTING NOW Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Potatoes On the 5th of September, 2023. The fourth engagement meeting took place at Makada (1). Sixteen Male participants were in attendance. Together with all the participants present, we went through the fourth module of the training manual. Which covers the aspect, of Pests, symptoms and Management. Pest have played a major role in reducing the yield of potato tubers in the field and the tubers preserved for storage in most rural communities. The farmers have been battling, with the problem of pests and how to control them for a very long period of time. The farmers paid attention to listen carefully to the discussion, since they are open to learning new ideas. Some of the farmers explained their own personal experiences that they have encountered with the pests and how they tried different chemicals without any improvement. In the caused of our discussions, we elaborated more on the five potato pests, symptoms and management. The participants were willing to implement the control methods we discussed and cultivate the habit of farm sanitation. In the end, the training session was educative and interactive. Bad roads. Availability of training manual to enhance effective learning.

Nigeria ACTING NOW Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Potatoes Report of Community Engagement Held on the 24th August, 2023. The fifth engagement meeting took place at Washen Community Bokkos, LGA with seventeen (17) female participants in attendance. The fifth module of the training manual covers the aspects of potato disease (viral and bacterial), symptoms and management. Generally, potato disease is not new to this community as it is one of the most difficult challenge the farmers have been struggling with over the years. Being a common manifestation in most of the farms here, it was easier for the farmers to follow up with the discussions. The farmers reported huge losses owing to some of the diseases discussed in the previous years and have seen no solution in sight yet. The major concern by the farmers is the early and late blight that has infested most of their farms of which they lack a control measure for. They added that these potato disease (early and late blight) have in some occasion led to complete plants failure. They mentioned different methods they have used in the past including application of different chemicals to control the disease but without any improvement. However, with their previous experience, the farmers are eager to learn new and innovative measures that will help bring an end to what they have been suffering from in the past. The farmers asked some few questions. such as; (1) what are the major ways of preventing early and late blight from spreading? (2) How can you identify the plant that is affected by late blight? (3) what are the method of controlling fusarium dry rot? I, responded by advising the farmers to apply the following; * use certified seed potato tubers. *Resistant varies should be sprayed when the first disease symptoms are noticed * fungicides should be applied at the recommended rate and preferably just before the onset of blight for effectiveness. Early planting enable plants to escape the worst time of blight. *Contact fungicides are used to coat the surface and stop the spread of the fungal disease. Examples, of contacts fungicides includes; Mancozeb, pencozeb, balear, plantineb, mancobex. Systematic fungicides enter the plants and kill the pathogens. Examples of systematic fungicides includes; Rodmil ( gold and plus) Fungi- pro, Fungicur, Monchamp, Metrostar, Parastar and Metalm 75 WP. Generally, our fifth encounter with the farmers was rewarding owning to the level of participation noted. Bad roads. Availability of training manual will enhance effective learning.
Nigeria ACTING NOW Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Potatoes On the 24th August, 2023. The fifth engagement meeting took place at Washen community bokkos LGA. Seventeen (17) male participants were in attendance. The fifth module of the training manual covers the aspects of potato disease, symptoms, management. And also potato Viral disease, symptoms and management. Potato disease is one of the most difficult challenges that the farmers had experience over the years. The disease were relatively, common to the farmers as they related it to there various farms. The farmers encountered a huge loss of potato yield in the previous years and are still battling with the disease up till date. There main concern are they early and late blight and the necessary measures to control it. These two diseases have been their major problems when it comes to potato disease. During the caused of our discussion the farmers voiced out, their experiences on the early and late blight which has damaged their farms and lead to total complete plants failure. The participants, later on explained how they have applied different chemicals to control the early and late blight without succeeding. However, since the farmers are anxious to learn new ideas and to find a way to tackle these potato diseases. The participants were willing to learn and implement the various control methods on their farmland. The farmers asked some few question during the regarding the various disease and (viral disease) we discussed such as: (1) what are they symptoms of bacteria wilt? (2) what are the steps of spraying fungicides in the case, of late blight? I responded by, advising the farmers to always practice seed bed hygiene. The farmers will notice the following symptoms: *Aboveground symptoms of bacterial wilt include wilting, stunting, and yellowing of the foliage in the field even during wet periods. *The rapid disease developed and the entire plants wilt quickly without yellowing. *Sections of diseased plants may wilt completely and dry up, while the remaining plant in the field appears healthy. *Leaves become yellow at their bases, then the whole plant wilts and dies. These are the following steps to take while applying the chemicals for potato late blight. Use a contact fungicide after plant emergence. â¢ Spray around 3g/liter (45â50 g/sprayer) of a systemic fungicide 2 weeks later; dosage can vary â¢ Subsequent sprays: Contact fungicides at 2-week intervals until the canopy turns yellow (maturity). If disease symptoms are visible in the field, spray a systemic fungicide (a maximum of two times per season for less susceptible varieties). In the end, the participants were enlightened. It was a participatory training session with the farmers. Bad roads. Availability of training manual will enhance effective learning.
Nigeria ACTING NOW Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Potatoes On the 25th August, 2023. The fifth engagement meeting took place at Kupiyel community bokkos, LGA. Fifteen (15) male participants were in attendance. The fifth module of the training manual covers the aspects of potato disease, symptoms, management and also potato Viral disease, symptoms and management. Potato disease is one of the most difficult challenges that the farmers had experience over the years. The disease were common to the farmers as they related it to their various farms. The farmers encountered a huge loss of potato yield in the previous, years and are still battling with the disease up till date. There main concern is the early and late blight and that have infested their farmlands.These two diseases have been their major problems when it comes to potato disease. During the caused of our discussion the farmers voiced out, their experiences on the early and late blight which has damaged their farms and lead to total complete plants failure. The participants, later on explained how they have applied different chemicals to control the early and late blight without achieving there goals. However, since the farmers are open to learning new ideas and to find a way to tackle these potato diseases. The participants were willing to learn and implement the various control methods on their farmland. The farmers asked some few question during the caused of our discussion such as; (1) What are the major causes of early and late blight? (2) Is there any specific chemicals to use so as, to tackle early and late blight? I responded, to the first question by explaining to the farmers about the two major causes of early and late blight. Early blight of potato is caused by fungal species while late blight is caused by oomycete( water mold) which is a distant relative of fungi. In the case, of early blight, the pathogen prefers a slightly warmer temperature while late blight the pathogens favour a moist and cool temperature . Contact fungicides are used to coat the surface and stop the spread of the fungal disease. Examples, of contacts fungicides includes; Mancozeb, pencozeb, balear, plantineb, mancobex. Systematic fungicides enter the plants and kill the pathogens. Examples of systematic fungicides includes; Rodmil ( gold and plus) Fungi- pro, Fungicur, Monchamp, Metrostar, Parastar and Metalm 75 WP. In the end, the farmers were delighted and willing to implement the various control methods listed on their individual farms. It was a demonstrative and participatory training session. Bad roads. Availability of training manual will enhance effective learning.

The fifth module of the training manual covers the aspects of potato disease (viral and bacterial), symptoms and management. Generally, potato disease is not new to this community as it is one of the most difficult challenge the farmers have been grappling with over the years. Being a common manifestation in most of the farms here, it was easier for the farmers to follow up with the discussions. They mentioned different methods they have used in the past including application of different chemicals to control the disease but without any success. However, with their previous experience, the farmers were opened to learning newer and innovative measures that will help bring an end to what they have been suffering from in the past. Several questions were also asked by the farmers such as: (1) How do you identify early blight in potato? (2)How do you treat early blight? I, responded to the question by laying more emphasis on the symptoms. Which includes, *Early blight can be identify by the presence of dark brown concentric lesions on older leaves. *As the spot enlarge, they may cause the entire leaf to yellow and die but remain on the plant. And for the second question. They early blight can be prevented by using fungicides to the plant and preventing the plant from constant wetting. And I listed the names of fungicide for the farmer. Example of systematic fungicides includes; Rodmil ( gold and plus) Fungi- pro, Fungicur, Monchamp, Metrostar, Parastar and Metalm 75 WP. Nigeria ACTING NOW Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Potatoes On the 27th August, 2023. The fifth engagement meeting held at Kupiyel community bokkos, LGA. Fifteen (15) female participants were in attendance. Together, with the participants present we went through the fifth module of the training manual. Which covers the aspects of potato diseases ( viral diseases) symptoms and management. Potato diseases are one of the most difficult challenges that farmers have been battling with for a very long period of time Participants, had reported immense economic losses over the years. Due to potato diseases and viral diseases, especially early and late blight. The farmers major challenge is the potato early blight and late blight. Potato early and late blight is the most economically important disease in Nigeria. Which has destroyed potato tubers and also lead to complete plant failure. In the, caused of our discussions the farmers, explained their different experiences. And how they have applied different chemicals to control the early and late blight without any positive outcome. The participants were determined to acquired more knowledge on how to prevent and control the early and late blight. During the caused of the training. They farmers asked several questions. Such as: (1) what if, the potato late blight is severe. How can a farmer control it? (2) What are the control measures in controlling common scab? I responded, to the first question by encouraging the farmers to use the Contact fungicides to prevent the spread of the disease. Example of contact fungicides includes; Mancozeb, Pencozeb, Balear (Tropic), Plantineb, Manesam, Mancobex, and Mancozan. Systematic fungicides enters into the plants and destroy the pathogens. Examples of systematic fungicides includes: Ridmoil( gold and plus) , fungi- pro, fungicur, Monchamp etc. I advised, the farmers on the quantity of chemical to use. If the late blight is severe, they should Measure one tin of milk or one and half . Spraying schedule should be done twice a week until the leaves turns yellow. As for the second question, I advised the farmers to practice crop rotation for 3- 5 years to reduce the severity of the disease, adequate moisture and proper timing of soil, farm management, use of resistant varieties in soils where the disease frequently occur. In the end, the farmers were delighted about the training and how it have open there minds to newer innovations. Bad roads. Availability of training manuals will enhance effective learning.
Nigeria ACTING NOW Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Potatoes On the 24th August, 2023. The fifth engagement meeting took place at Washen Community Bokkos, LGA with thirteen (13) youth participants in attendance. The fifth module of the training manual covers the aspects of potato disease (viral and bacterial), symptoms and management. Generally, potato disease is common to this community. As it is one of the most difficult challenge the farmers have been struggling with over the years. Since, it is a common issue most farmers have experience on their various farms, it was easier for the farmers to follow up with the discussions. The farmers reported huge economical losses because of some of the diseases discussed, in the previous years and have seen no solution. The major concern by the farmers is the early and late blight that has damage their farms of which they lack a control measure for. Although, the farmers had applied different chemicals on their farms, and yet no remedy. However, with their previous experience, the farmers were opened to learning newer and innovative measures that will help bring an end to what they have been suffering from in the past. During the caused of our training the farmers asked some questions. Such as: (1) what are the causes of early and late blight? (2) How can early and late blight be prevent? I responded, to the first question. By laying more emphasis on the what causes early and late blight. Early blight is caused by fungal species. While late blight of potato is a disease caused by oomycetes, which is a distant relative of fungi. In potato early blight, the pathogen prefers a slightly warmer temperature in the range of 24 - 29 degrees. while in potato late blight, the pathogen favors a moist and cool temperature in the range of 12- 18 degrees. Prolonged period of wetness on the plants. While the spores tend to spread in cool and wet conditions in late blight. It has a small impact on the plants in Early blight. While the plants are severely affected and damage in potato late blight. Early and late blight can be prevents by the following. For early blight * Timely spraying of two major chemicals *Practicing proper field sanitation. Crop rotation, using clean seeds, and roguing, the disease can be prevented. * Contact fungicides are used to coat the surface and stop the spread of the disease. * When disease symptoms are present, systemic chemicals are typically used for treatment. For late blight: *Crop rotation of 1 to 7 seasons to eliminate the disease from the soil Use of tolerant or resistance varieties * Field and store sanitation-clean and disinfect all tools and equipment for handling potato tubers *Use certified seed potato tubers Dehaulm the crop to ensure good skin development and ensure minimal bruising of tubers during harvesting or grading. The pathogen can only enter the tuber through a wound or cut. * As a preventive measure, susceptible potato varieties are sprayed with fungicide at recommended rates (Ridomil, Cabrio duo, Glory, Blue Snow). * Fungicides must be applied at the recommended rate and preferably just before the onset of blight for effectiveness. Early planting enables plants to escape the peak time of blight. * Resistant varieties should be sprayed when the first disease symptoms are noticed. * Bi-weekly applications are normal. However, the frequency of application depends on the severity of the infestation and the weather. It is important to spray on the underside of the leaves. Lastly, the training session was interactive and educative. The farmers were willing to implement the new ideas on their various farms. Bad roads. Availability of training manual will enhance effective learning.
Nigeria ACTING NOW Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Potatoes On the 24th August, 2023. The fifth engagement meeting took place at Washen Community Bokkos, LGA with eleven (11) youth participants in attendance. The fifth module of the training manual covers the aspects of potato disease (viral and bacterial), symptoms and management. Generally, potato disease is common to this community. As it is one of the most difficult challenge the farmers have been struggling with over the years. Since, it is a common issue most farmers have experience on their various farms, it was easier for the farmers to follow up with the discussions. The farmers reported huge economical losses because of some of the diseases discussed, in the previous years and have seen no solution. The major concern by the farmers is the early and late blight that has damage their farms of which they lack a control measure for. Although, the farmers had applied different chemicals on their farms, and yet no remedy. However, with their previous experience, the farmers were opened to learning newer and innovative measures that will help bring an end to what they have been suffering from in the past. During the caused of our training the farmers asked some questions. Such as: (1) What are the major causes of early and late blight? (2) What are the steps to control late blight? I responded, to the first question. By laying more emphasis on the what causes early and late blight. Early blight is caused by fungal species. While late blight of potato is a disease caused by oomycetes, which is a distant relative of fungi. In potato early blight, the pathogen prefers a slightly warmer temperature in the range of 24 - 29 degrees. while in potato late blight, the pathogen favors a moist and cool temperature in the range of 12- 18 degrees. Prolonged period of wetness on the plants. While the spores tend to spread in cool and wet conditions in late blight. It has a small impact on the plants in Early blight. While the plants are severely affected and damage in potato late blight. Steps to control late blight includes: Timely spraying of two major groups of chemicals to prevent infection and kill the pathogen after infection: * Contact fungicides kill by contact. Examples: Mancozeb, Pencozeb, Balear (Tropic), Plantineb, Manesam, Mancobex, and Mancozan. * Systemic fungicides enter the plant and kill the pathogen. Examples: Ridomil (Gold and Plus), Fungi-Pro, Fungicur, Monchamp, Metalm 75 WP, Metrostar and Parastar. In the end, the farmers are willing to implement the new innovations on their various farms. It was an interactive session. Bad roads. Availability of training manual will enhance effective learning.
Nigeria ACTING NOW Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Potatoes On 27th August, 2023.The fifth engagement meeting took place at Kupiyel Community Bokkos, LGA with ten (10) youth participants in attendance. The fifth module of the training manual covers the aspects of potato disease symptoms, management and viral disease. Generally, potato disease is not new to this community as it is one of the most difficult challenge the farmers have been battling with over the years. Being a common manifestation in most of the farms here, it was easier for the farmers to follow up with the discussions. The farmers reported huge losses owing to some of the diseases discussed in the previous years and have seen no remedy in sight yet. The major concern by the farmers is the early and late blight that has destroyed their farms of which they tried different control measures and yet no positive outcome. They added that these potato disease (early and late blight) have in some occasion led to complete plants failure. They mentioned different methods they have used in the past including application of different chemicals to control the disease but without any success. However, with their previous experience, the farmers were opened to learning newer and innovative measures that will help bring and end to what they have been suffering from in the past. A participant asked a question during the caused of our discussions: (1) Is there any specific chemical for controlling early and late blight? I responded, to this question by informing the farmers that the fungicide for destroying blight has not been discovered yet. But there are some fungicides, that they can apply at the recommendable rate to prevent and control early and late blight. There are contact and systematic fungicides ,the farmers can use, and the quantity to measure. However, most farmers make the common mistakes of applying two chemical of the same category. Instead of applying two major fungicides of different category. For example, a farmer will purchase two chemical that is systematic and mix both together and spray on his or her farm. But the right thing to do is to purchase contact and systematic fungicides. Contact fungicides will prevent the pathogens from spreading while the systematic fungicides will enter inside the plants and kill the pathogens. The quantity to measure, I advised the farmers to use five(5) tea spoons of contact fungicides and mix it with water before the disease starts manifesting. But when the disease is severe the farmers are advised to measure one tin of peak milk or one and half of systematic fungicides so as, to kill the pathogens. Examples of contact fungicides includes: Mancozeb, Pencozeb, Balear (Tropic), Plantineb, Manesam, Mancobex, and Mancozan. Examples of systematic fungicides includes: Ridomil (Gold and Plus), Fungi-Pro, Fungicur, Monchamp, Metalm 75 WP, Metrostar and parastar. In the end, the farmers are willing and eager to implement what they had learned on their various farmers. Indeed, it was an interactive training session. Persistent rainfall. That leads to poor turnout for the training. Availability of training manual with enhance effective learning.

Nigeria ACTING NOW Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Potatoes On the 5th September, 2023. The fifth engagement meeting took place at Makada (1)Community Bokkos, LGA with sixteen (16) male participants in attendance. The fifth module of the training manual covers the aspects of potato disease (viral and bacterial), symptoms and management. Potato disease is not new to this community as it is one of the most difficult challenge the farmers have been struggling with over the years. Since, it is a common situation in most of the farms here, it was easier for the farmers to follow up with the discussions. The farmers reported huge losses caused by the diseases in the previous years and have not seen any solution yet. The major concerns by the farmers is the early and late blight that has afflict their farms. The farmers had applied different chemicals to prevent and control the blight without succeeding. They added that these potato disease (early and late blight) have in some occasion led to complete plants failure. They mentioned different methods they have used in the past including application of different chemicals to control the disease but without any success. However, with their previous experience, the farmers were consenting to learning new ideas that will help bring an end to what they have been suffering from in the past. Several questions were also asked by the farmers such as: (1) What are the major causes of early and late blight ? I responded, to the question by explaining to the participants more about the cause of the blight. I clarified to the farmers that potato early blight is caused by fungal species. It caused by fungus, the pathogens prefers a slightly warmer temperature. The blight affects mostly the older leaves that gradually spread to the stem and leaves gradually. However, the early blight has a small impact on plants and a long period of wetness on the plants will worsen the situation. While the potato late blight, is a disease caused by oomycetes ( smaller spores mold) which is a distant relative of fungi. The pathogens favours a moist and cool temperature in the range of 12- 18 degree centigrade, that is around (July- August). Irregular shaped lesions (any localize abnormal structural change in a bodily part) on the leaves, petioles, and stems. The potato tubers start to rot, a whitish cottony growth of fungus is visible on the whole plant. The plant are severely affected and damaged and the spores tend to spread in cool and wet conditions. Lastly, the farmers were willing to practice all the new innovation on their various farms. It was an interactive session. Bad roads Availability of training manuals will enhance effective learning.

The discussions, went smoothly because the farmers have ideas on the topic of discussion and they were able to relate them to their already existing practices.We discussed about the different types of irrigation farming, advantages and disadvantages. Most farmers practice non ridges irrigation farming, whereby generators are used to distribute water through pipes to the whole farm. In the caused of our discussions i introduced to the farmers; furrow, and drip irrigation farming. Which was new to them. The farmers, were amazed by the new types of irrigation farming which was introduced to them. The participants also complained about the expenses of purchasing the sprinter. I encouraged them to use the sprinter caused it can spray a wider space and there is less use of man power. Water irrigation farming is very essential to the farmers. Since they can not wait until the dry season is over before they can start farming. Farming is the major source of income of the people in this particular community so irrigation farming system helps improved soil texture. Lastly, the training session was participatory. Poor turnout for the training. Availability of training manuals will enhance effective learning.

Nigeria ACTING NOW Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Potatoes On the 16th September, 2023. The sixth engagement meeting held at Makada (1) community bokkos LGA. Fourteen (14) male participants were in attendance. The sixth module of the training manual covers the aspects of water irrigation management, types, advantages and disadvantages. Generally, irrigation farming is not new to this community as most of the locals have been practicing this system of farming over the years. And it has helped in increasing their livelihood and in the aspects of seed production too. Being a common practice by the farmers,it was easier for the farmers to follow up with the discussions. The participants were familiar with most of the types of irrigation farming except the furrow, which is different from the common types they have been practicing. The farmers were eager to implement the new idea they have learned on their farmlands. Lastly, the session was interactive and participatory. Bad roads. Availability of training manual will enhance effective learning.

Nigeria ACTING NOW Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Potatoes On the 16th September, 2023. The sixth engagement meeting held at Makada (1) community bokkos LGA. Fifteen (15) female participants were in attendance. Of interest, was the module covered (Module six), which we looked at water irrigation management, types, advantages and disadvantages of irrigation farming. Irrigation farming system is common to the farmers in this community, because they have been practicing these system of farming for a long period of time. The major occupation of the people in this community is farming so they cultivate their lands all through the year. Since the farmers can't wait for another raining season, they will have to practice irrigation farming. In order to earn a living. Participants paid keen interest through out the course of discussion and were eager to try out some of the new types of irrigation farming. However, some of the farmers complained about the expenses of practicing some of the irrigation farming system. Such as: the sprinter and drip irrigation. Lastly, the farmers were anxious and willing to implement the new innovative ideas they have learned. It was a participatory training session. Bad roads. Availability of training manuals will enhance effective learning

The training was a huge success and the trainers have learned something new that they will improve on their farming this season. We sincerely appreciate your effort SOLIDARIDAD. We give GOD the glory... The major challenges are, the farmers time, transportation and rainfall sometime it affects the class. For this training to move forward, I suggest that please SOLIDARIDAD should help this farmers that are being trained with this items at subsidies rate, quality seeds, fungicides, fertilizer, good storage facilities like Diffuse Light Store DLS store and a market. In communities that I train farmers Mabel, kulias and Fakkos. I understand that the farmers produced potatoes in large quantities but there is no market for them to sale at a good price. I solicit for the farmers to SOLIDARIDAD to help the trainers to have better market price and that will make the training move forward. GOD BLESS SOLIDARIDAD...

Nigeria ACTING NOW NI Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Potatoes On the 30th September, 2023. The seventh engagement meeting took place at Makada I community bokkos LGA. Seven (7) female participants were in attendance. Together, with all the participants present. We went through the seventh module of the training manual. which covers the aspects of harvesting and post harvest management. The farmers were familiar with these particular concepts, except for some few concepts which are not too common to the farmers. Since the participants were open to learning new ideas the paid keen attention to the discussions and were able to relate them to their already existing farms. In the caused of our discussions, the participants voiced out their various challenges they had encountered when it comes to harvesting and storing of potatoes in the stores. Diffused light store, and dehaulming are concepts that were new to the farmers. I encouraged the farmers to adapt the new concepts inorder to get more better tubers free from disease and cutting during harvesting on the farms. And also from diseases and pest that affects tubers in the stores Finally, it was an interactive and participatory session. It ended in praise and appreciation from the farmers. Poor turnout for the training. Availability of training manuals will enhance effective learning.

Nigeria ACTING NOW NI Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Potatoes On the 29th September, 2023. The seventh engagement meeting held at Washen community bokkos LGA. Fifteen (15) male participants were in attendance. The seventh module of the training manual, covers the aspects of harvesting and post harvest management. The farmers were familiar with these particular concepts; except for some concepts which are not too common to the farmers. But since the participants were open to learning new ideas the paid keen attention to have a grasp of the discussions. And they were able to easily relate them to their already existing farms. During the caused, of our discussions the farmers voiced out their various challenges they had encountered when it comes to harvesting and storing of potatoes in the stores. Most farmers have been grappling with huge loss in stores. Because of lack of knowledgeable ideas of storing tubers in the stores. The diffused light store and dehaulming; are the concept which were new to the farmers. Inconclusion, the farmers have learned a newer innovative ideas that will help them on their various farms and stores.I encouraged the farmers to adapt the new concepts which was introduced to them. So as, to harvest clean tubers free from disease, cutting, and injuries on the farms. And also to practice preventive measures of storing tubers free from disease, pest and predators. It was an interactive and participatory session. Bad road. Availability of training manual will enhance effective learning.

Nigeria NISCOPS NI Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Oil Palm A total of 32 participants were trained for 2 days, first day was a classroom training while the second day was a field and practical training session, made up of 26 males and 6 females from Wilmar Out-grower farmers and SWA. They were trained on the five packages of BMP and SLU. They are in turn, to go and do peer-peer training for their farmers in their communities. Rain on the second day caused some delays and hastened up the field activities. A follow up with farmers will be conducted to monitor compliance.
Nigeria NISCOPS NI Meetings Oil Palm Participants present made commitments to support the implemention of the Sustainable Management Plan (SMP). Stakeholders pledged to synergize with smallholder farmers and relevant authorities at the State and LGA levels in actualizing the goal of Sustainable and Climate Smart Oil Palm Development in the State. Stakeholders maintained that there is the need for an increased advocacy on forest protection and conservation as well as found worthiness in championing a push for Women and Youths to own Productive Assets especially those that will strengthen their economic resilience. There were minimal challenges faced, however, those invited from the hard to reach areas of the State couldn't arrive early enough making the meeting to start later than supposed. There should be a review meeting of the commitments made by Stakeholders so as to monitor the pace and any possible challenges the respective MSPs may be facing in the implemention of the Sustainable Management Plan (SMP) in their own location. MSP Coordinators could initiate Community Engagement opportunities with the gatekeepers on the issue of Productive Assets for Women and Youths and report success stories. The MSP Coordinators in Collaboration with Solidaridad Team should establish a relationship with the Local Government Service Commission and the State House of Assembly Committee on Agriculture.
Nigeria NISCOPS NI Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Oil Palm Staff and Students of Akwa Ibom state University were trained on vegetable production which included nursery practices and field preparation. A total of 225 participants were involved, with 6 being staff (3 males and 3 Females) and 219 being students (104 Males and 115 Females). The training is aimed at the participants having the skills to go into agribusiness as an alternative livelihood. The major challenge was the large number of participants, which was not easy to control and get everyone's attention . There was also the challenge of whether and choice of site for the planting; the site has poor soil was that not immediately factored into the process, resulting in poor germination. However, the ones planted on bags did well. The training schedule should be timed to correspond with the right period for vegetable cultivation in the choosen location. Also, the number of participants should be trimmed for easy management per session.

Nigeria NISCOPS NI Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Oil Palm A total of 30 participants attended the workshop from both Akwa Ibom state and Cross River State (17 males and 13 females) from the states Ministries of Agriculture, Environment, Forestry Commission, States legislation (House Committees on Agriculture and Environment), Farmers Associations, CSOs, Big Plantation Owners, and the Press. The objectives of the workshop were presented. The oil palm landscapes and Green Growth were discussed. Dialogue on Akwa Ibom and Cross River States Green Growth fact sheets and Policies were discussed. Participants then worked in groups to draw up states' Green Growth Plans. The need for participants to enhance Solidaridad visit with the states Governors or the Secretary to the states Governors was emphasized. The Legislators from Akwa Ibom state couldn't attend for reasons not communicated. There needs to be a follow up with the participants to push the Green Growth Plans to their respective states governments. Nigeria NISCOPS NI Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Oil Palm 23 participants, drawn from the four NISCOPS states, made up of 4 females and 19 males from the public sector, MSP and Community Facilitators. The workshop reviewed and fine tuned existing community based forest protection plans and explored the opportunities for promoting agroforestry intervention. Part of the objectives also included building on the existing Carbon Credit concept Note (2022) and aligned this with the draft CFPP. It also enhanced participants' knowledge on the dynamics of inclusive agroforestry practices for climate resilience and sustainable landscape management. The two day training ended with a field visit to two selected agroforestry farms in a community in Ikom LGA. The participants saw what and how an Agroforestry farm should be like and also demonstrated agroforestry by planting native species of tree crops in the farm Two participants from Akwa Ibom and Cross River States Ministry of Agriculture and an MSP member couldn't attend due to official engagement. They however sent representatives. One of the farms selected for the demo on Agroforestry was not well planned as the plant population and spacing was too poor. Correction was given for the benefit of the farmer and participants The LGA Directors of Agriculture as well as the Community Facilitators are to engage relevant stakeholders in their areas to draw up an Agroforestry plan, to be inclusive and sustainable.
Nigeria NISCOPS NI Items Distribution Oil Palm 4 litres of Alion, a pre-emergence herbicide, was distributed to 11 Community Facilitators, after training them on its handling and application. These Facilitators are to distribute these herbicides to 45 farmers (Akwa Ibom; 15, Cross River; 25, Enugu 2; and Kogi; 3). These quantities distributed will enhance sustainable land management of 76.5ha in the project communities. NIL The Community Facilitators will distribute these herbicides (100mil per farmer) to preselected beneficiaries who will be trained on its uses and handling through a peer-peer training.

Nigeria SGDP1 Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Potatoes This training centres on the background to the potato industry. After the training farmers were made to understand the origin, the nutritional value, ecological requirements for potato production. Also farmers were made to understand the consumption and uses of potato, potato growing areas in Nigeria, potato value chain stakeholders, opportunities for potato sector, challenges and climate change effect on potato production. Sierra Leone BAFS Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Cocoa Cashew Coffee The topics discussed during the training session have enhanced participants to be gainfully aware of the opportunity and challenges to promote the quality management practices and marketing of the cocoa, coffee and cashew economy. Sierra Leone BAFS Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Cashew The training is essential as it provides the basis for capacity building and outline the structures of the FSCs and the role of members in the functionality of the FSCs scheme. The timing of the training was not appropriate for a few farmers as they were engaged in their upland rice cultivation, however the participants were able to block time to attend the training. Engagement with farmers to state the timeline of the training to ensure adequate participation of farmers.
Sierra Leone BAFS Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Cashew Coffee Cocoa The training has outlined the concept and functional activities of the FSCs to its beneficiaries. Many farmers find it difficult in accessing markets to purchase their farm tools, inputs, tools and services but the bases of this training have heralded the exposition of farmers to tackle the bottleneck in accessing inputs and services by linkage to the farmers support centers. The majority of the participants were late for the training despite being a community-based training and as such the training was delayed to start on time. The training should be done twice a year depending on the availability of funds especially during the planting season for inputs support.
Sierra Leone BAFS Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Cocoa Cashew Coffee The output of the training on the farmer support centre has impacted the knowledge and awareness of farmers on the operation of the farmer's support centre and the services it can offer to enhance sustainable production in their farming activities. Mobilisation of participants to attend the training was a bit challenging despite it being community-based training. Follow-up training should be done subsequently during the planting season thus leveraging the support of the FSCs for immediate inputs and services for farmers.
Sierra Leone BAFS Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Cocoa Cashew Coffee The training was essential as because it is a capacity-building platform and it has helped farmers to be abreast of the functions of the FSCs in providing inputs supplies and services to maximise production. The period stated for the training was a bit challenging because few farmers were not present at the time of the training due to the activities of the upland rice cultivation. Engagement with farmers to state their convenient time within the stipulated implementation period of the project for maximum participation.
Sierra Leone BAFS Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Cashew The training facilitated was interactive and participatory. The practical installation of the improved cashew processing facilities has complemented participants on the technical knowledge of the functions of the various components of the processing facilities The schedule for the training was not enough as there was a break-off as a result of the observation of the National independent day. However, the training modules were completed . Despite the training being purely based on practical sessions, there is a need for the provision of the training manual in subsequent training.
Sierra Leone BAFS Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Cocoa Cashew Coffee The Sierra Leone Cocoa, Coffee, Cashew Platform (SLCCCP)workshop is essential thus far in bringing key sector players within the Cocoa, coffee and cashew value chain to dialogue on challenges and provides solutions in revitalizing the CCC sectors. The 2 days allocated to this workshop were not enough for the workshop. However, the various consultants were able to complete the workshop session beyond the stipulated time. Allocation of more days to this SLCCCP workshop to dialogue on important cross-cutting issues within the tree crops sector.

Sierra Leone SLADF Training/Capacity Building/Workshop Maize Oil Palm Cocoa The conclusions of the training are: 1. The training was considered to be timely especially when most of the Agribusiness have recruited new staff while for others it was an added advantage to properly Keep them abreast with key aspects of the Outgrower model concept. 2. With the skills acquired in preparing the scheme support calendar and cropping calendar, field staff will now apply ideas learnt from the workshop and functionalise the Outgrower scheme within their respective agribusiness companies. The key challenge faced was that most CEOs and managers of agribusinesses were most reluctant to allow other members in the organization to attend capacity training rolled out by service provider instead they attend all by themselves. 1. Grantee heads are encouraged to be sending other members of the company to the training instead of monopolising the opportunity. 2. Project staff at supervisory level in SCADeP and Solidaridad to follow up on in the post-training action plan and ensure compliance of agribusinesses to move the schemes forward
